Steps to be followed while using **phpMyAdmin** :

## **Step 1: Install WAMP**

Download WAMP and phpMyAdmin from [http://www.wampserver.com/en/](http://www.wampserver.com/en/)

Once installed, be sure the Wampserver is running.  The WAMP icon in the lower right side of the windows taskbar should appear green indicating everything is working.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Also, test the Localhost capability by typing localhost in the browser. The results should be:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Figure 3: WampServer Configuration

## **Step 2: Connect to phpMyAdmin**

From above screen, click on the phpMyAdmin. This tool can be used to manage the database on the local system. phpMyAdmin is used to run the stored procedure, to generate the required data for PBBT app. The opening page should look something like this:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Figure 4: PhpMyAdmin login page

The username is &quot;root&quot; and the password is blank at this point.

In a production environment, a different username with a strong password must be used.

The PhpMyAdmin application looks like the following:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

## **Step 3: Creating a new database**

Click on &quot;New&quot; and give a name for the database, Collation as the option from dropdown and click on &quot;Create&quot;.

Using PhpMyAdmin, create a database:

## **Step 4: Upload csv files**

The steps detailed below gives an overview of how to upload csv files-

1. Create the structure. (executed in SQL tab of phpMyAdmin via Stored Procedures shown in Step 3)
2. Type in the code given below to import the csv file

For creating the structure of the tables used, run the stored procedure in the SQL tab of phpMyAdmin –

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

All the tables will be created with a structure similar to the current csv files.

| **CSV folder/file name** | **Naming convention used in Stored procedure** |
| --- | --- |
| Finance - Salaries and Wages |   |
| f1112\_f1a | public |
| f1112\_f2 | private\_nonprofit |
| f1112\_f3 | private\_profit |
| Institution characteristics - schools Dictionary Information (hd2012) | schools |
| 12 Month Enrollment - Credit Hours (efia2012\_rv) | credithours |
| 12 Month Enrollment - Unduplicated Headcount (effy2012\_rv) | unduplicatedheadcount |
| Completions, Awards, Degrees Conferred (c2012\_a\_rv) | completions |
| Default Rate (default rate 11-13) | defaultRate |
| Employees by Assigned Position (eap2012\_rv) | employeebyassignedposition |
| Graduation Rates (gr2012\_rv) | graduationrate |
| Instructional Staff - # and Salary Outlays (sal2012\_is\_rv) | instructionalstaff |
| Non-Instructional Staff - # and Salary Outlays (sal2012\_nis\_rv) | noninstructionalstaff |



Now to upload the csv files, just execute the following command either via SQL tab of phpMyAdmin page –

**LOAD DATA LOCAL INFILE &#39;C:/path/to/csv/file/dataTable.csv&#39;**

**INTO TABLE &lt;tablename&gt;**

**FIELDS TERMINATED BY &#39;,&#39;**

**ENCLOSED BY &#39;&quot;&#39;**

**LINES TERMINATED BY &#39;\n&#39;**

**IGNORE 1 ROWS;**

SQL tab of the phpMyAdmin screen –

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

## **Step 4: Run Stored Procedure**

**How to save stored procedure queries in database –**

1.
  1. Select the database.
  2. Click on SQL tab
  3. Copy the stored procedure of the required year from the file below (Data mart initial loading -&gt; stored procedure2012).
  4. Click on go button to save the stored procedure.

 ![](./) ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Once these stored procedures are created, these should be executed or ran to create the final table. This can be done by two different ways,

1. **a.** After the stored procedure script is run, select the database on which the procedure is created and then type &#39;Call (stored procedure name) **OR**
2. **b.**  the stored procedure can be run by selecting it and then clicking the &quot;Execute&quot; option.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Following is the order in which the stored procedure should be ran –

1. Schools
2. Carnegie
3. Finance
4. DefaultRate
5. Student
6. Employee
7. School Summary Table

### **How to run via Command Prompt**

## **Step 1: Locate the path – database**

Search for **WAMP** from the windows search bar after installation. Right click on it and click on open file location. It will generally lead to a place where the shortcut for WAMP server is stored. Again, click on WAMP server and click on open file location. Navigate to the path highlighted.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

## **Step 2: Connect to MySQL from command prompt**

Goto your command prompt, and copy the path where mysql is located (shown in Step 2).

In my case, this is the path - C:\xampp\mysql\bin

So give the command where your mysql is located,

Ex:   **cd C:\xampp\mysql\bin**

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Now, inorder to connect to mysql, from localhost, give in the following command

You can give the following command - **mysql -u root -p -h 127.0.0.1.**

The root is the user and by default, we don&#39;t need to type in any password for user root. You will be prompted to enter password, just hit Enter and you will get connected to the database.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

## **Step 3: Find or Create Database**

To see all the databases in mysql, type in the command **show databases;**

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

To create a database, simply type in **create database &lt;database**** name&gt;;**

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

To use the database to create tables, type in **use &lt;database name&gt;;**

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

To see the tables, within the database, type in **show tables;**

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

In the command prompt, type in **call create\_raw\_ipeds\_table\_structure()**; ![](data:image/*;base64,)
